{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, chapter 16 (\"Kali\" / \"The Bud\").**[^1]\n\nThe bud is first described opening at dawn:\n\n> When Dawn its rosy cheek has shown,  \n> The bud's gold breast is open thrown.[^2]\n\nIt drinks morning light from the sun's goblet and tears open its breast:\n\n> It sips on splendor in the tavern of morn,  \n> Its life from the **Sun's own goblet** is born.[^3]  \n>   \n> Before the Sun, **it tears its breast apart**,  \n> What blissful pleasure for its tiny heart![^4]\n\nThe speaker then prays:\n\n> Let me behold my Sun, though far it seems,  \n> **And like a bud, be wrapped within its beams**.[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 16 (\"Kali\"), [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/16-kali/translation/).\n[^2]: Ibid., [¶9](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/16-kali/translation/#p-a8fce0).\n[^3]: Ibid., [¶84](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/16-kali/translation/#p-ae86d8).\n[^4]: Ibid., [¶172](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/16-kali/translation/#p-99fffa).\n[^5]: Ibid., [¶601](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/16-kali/translation/#p-44ef90).",
